. Malden, MA: Blackwell Publishers. {{ISBN|0-631-20504-7}}. Readings/Anthologies\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikibooks|Japanese|Grammar/Transitivity|Transitivity}}\n* [http://www.sljfaq.org/afaq/afaq.html FAQ] for <code>sci.lang.japan</code>.\n* [http://grammar.nihongoresources.com/ Nihongoresources grammar book]<!--\n* [http://learnjapanese.elanguageschool.net/course/view.php?id=7 Japanese Grammar Lessons]&nbsp;\u2013 Comprehensive Japanese grammar lessons. Does this still exist? (And if so, is it any good?) -->\n* [http://www.guidetojapanese.org/learn/grammar Tae Kim's Guide to Learning Japanese] Japanese grammar guide\n* Shoko Hamano, [http://www.gwu.edu/~eall/vjg/vjghomepage/vjghome.htm ''Visualizing Japanese Grammar'']&nbsp;\u2013 Animated Japanese grammar lessons from George Washington University.\n*[http://www.learnjapanesefree.com/basic-japanese-grammar.html On particles in Japanese]\n\n{{Japanese language}}\n{{Language grammars}} \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Japanese Grammar}}\n[[Category:Japanese grammar|*]]\n[[Category:Grammars of specific languages]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fixing, replaced: runs though  \u2192  runs through", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_grammar"}
{"title_page": "X-Men Fairy Tales", "text_new": "{{Infobox comic book title|  <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|image=X-Men Fairy Tales.jpg\n|caption=Cover to ''X-Men Fairy Tales'' #1 (July 2006).  Art by [[Sana Takeda]].\n|schedule=monthly\n|limited=y\n|publisher=[[Marvel Comics]]\n|date= July 2006-October 2006\n|issues=4\n|main_char_team=\n|writers=[[C. B. Cebulski]]\n|artists=[[Sana Takeda]]\n|pencillers=\n|inkers=\n|letterers=[[Tom Valente]]\n|colorists=\n|creative_team_month=\n|creative_team_year=\n|creators=\n|subcat=X-Men\n|limsub=Marvel Comics\n|sort=X-Men Fairy Tales\n}}\nThe '''''X-Men Fairy Tales''''' is a 4-part mini-series that was created by ex-editor [[C. B. Cebulski]], with art by [[Sana Takeda]].<ref>[http://www.thexaxis.com/minis/fairytales1.htm Overview] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027155512/http://www.thexaxis.com/minis/fairytales1.htm |date=October 27, 2007 }}- Overview</ref> It was published by [[Marvel Comics]] in [[2006 in comics|2006]].\n\nThe 4-part [[Limited series (comics)|mini-series]] seeks to re-enact the adventures told throughout the original [[X-Men]] comics, just through folk lore and fairy tales instead.<ref>[http://www.forbiddenplanet.co.uk/index.php?main_page=product_music_info&products_id=33909 fairy tales]- Fairy Tales</ref> It was the first of the [[Marvel Fairy Tales]] which went to tell similar stories for other Marvel titles.\n\n== Release information ==\nWhen X-Men Fairy Tales Volume 1 came out, it was sold out by May 2006.<ref>[http://www.marvel.com/news/comicstories.440.X-Men_Fairy_Tales_Sellout Sellout Date]-Sellout Date</ref> Shortly thereafter Volume 2 hit the shelves on June 21, 2006.<ref>[http://www.marvel.com/catalog/?id=4320 Number 2 Release]- Number 2 Release</ref>\n\n== Part 1 ==\n\n=== Specs ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Release Date\n! Written By\n! Art By \n! # of Pages\n|-\n| May 17, 2006\n| C.B.Cebulski\n| Sana Takeda\n| 32 Full Color Pages\n|}\n\n=== Description ===\n\nThis volume re-enacts the old tale of [[Momotar\u014d]].  It sets the X-Men into this story to play out the traditional roles of the characters within the original.  Within the story, Momotaro has the abilities of the X-Man [[Cyclops (Marvel Comics)|Cyclops]], allowing him to shoot beams from his eyes.  Because of this ability he remains in seclusion, until a great monk comes to him (symbolism as Professor X came to him during the original X-Men series) and convinces him to use his power for good.  From this, they go off to defeat a horde of demons.<ref>[http://comics.ign.com/articles/702/702993p1.html Volume One]- Volume One</ref>\n\n== Part 2 ==\n\n=== Specs ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Release Date\n! Written By\n! Art By \n! # of Pages\n|-\n| June 21, 2006\n| C.B.Cebulski\n| Kyle Baker\n| 32 Full Color Pages\n|}\n\n=== Description ===\n\nThis volume retells the ancient story called \"The Friendship of the Tortoise and the Eagle\".  It replays the old story of how Magneto and Professor Xavier originally met, but it's played through as the story of the fairy tale.<ref>[http://comics.ign.com/articles/709/709426p1.html Number 2]- Number 2</ref>\n\n== Part 3 ==\n\n=== Specs ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Release Date\n! Written By\n! Art By \n! # of Pages\n|-\n| July 7, 2006\n| C.B.Cebulski\n| Bill Sienkiewicz\n| 32 Full Color Pages\n|}\n\n=== Description ===\n\nA blind Cyclops awakens the princess ([[Jean Grey]]) from her sleep, only to find that Wolverine is determined to keep her under her spell, or worse, dead.\n\n== Part 4 ==\n\n=== Specs ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Release Date\n! Written By\n! Art By \n! # of Pages\n|-\n| October, 2006\n| C.B.Cebulski\n| Kei Kobayashi\n| 32 Full Color Pages\n|}\n\n=== Description ===\nPulling upon some fairy tales that originated in [[New Orleans]], the love between [[Gambit (comics)|Gambit]] and [[Rogue (comics)|Rogue]] is re-created, though the roles are reversed, with Rogue/Anna as the ghost-communicating thief and Gambit on the side of the law with his partner, [[Bishop (comics)|Bishop]]. Mystique takes the form of the voodoo witch that sells Rogue's talent, along with her other daughter, Irene. Coming home after closing, Rogue is surprised to have a customer, [[Emma Frost]] asking for her services. It is then that Emma's intent is not to communicate with the dead, but to control them, and she, along with the members of Hellfire will stop at nothing do so.<ref>[http://www.marvel.com/catalog/?id=4476 Part 3]- Part 3</ref><ref>[http://www.popcultureshock.com/reviews.php?id=5663 Part 3 - 2nd ref] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071210030602/http://www.popcultureshock.com/reviews.php?id=5663 |date=December 10, 2007 }}- 2nd Ref</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{comicbookdb|type=title|id=6935|title=''X-Men Fairy Tales''}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.coverbrowser.com/covers/x-men-fairy-tales Cover Art] - The cover art for the 4 comics.\n\n{{X-Comics}}\n\n[[Category:Comics based on fairy tales]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox comic book title|  <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics--> \n|title=X-Men Fairy Tales\n|image=X-Men Fairy Tales.jpg\n|caption=Cover to ''X-Men Fairy Tales'' #1 (July 2006).  Art by [[Sana Takeda]].\n|schedule=monthly\n|limited=y\n|publisher=[[Marvel Comics]]\n|date= July 2006-October 2006\n|issues=4\n|main_char_team=\n|writers=[[C. B. Cebulski]]\n|artists=[[Sana Takeda]]\n|pencillers=\n|inkers=\n|letterers=[[Tom Valente]]\n|colorists=\n|creative_team_month=\n|creative_team_year=\n|creators=\n|subcat=X-Men\n|limsub=Marvel Comics\n|sort=X-Men Fairy Tales\n}}\nThe '''''X-Men Fairy Tales''''' is a 4-part mini-series that was created by ex-editor [[C. B. Cebulski]], with art by [[Sana Takeda]].<ref>[http://www.thexaxis.com/minis/fairytales1.htm Overview] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027155512/http://www.thexaxis.com/minis/fairytales1.htm |date=October 27, 2007 }}- Overview</