e and the Eagle\".  It replays the old story of how Magneto and Professor Xavier originally met, but it's played through as the story of the fairy tale.<ref>[http://comics.ign.com/articles/709/709426p1.html Number 2]- Number 2</ref>\n\n== Part 3 ==\n\n=== Specs ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Release Date\n! Written By\n! Art By \n! # of Pages\n|-\n| July 7, 2006\n| C.B.Cebulski\n| Bill Sienkiewicz\n| 32 Full Color Pages\n|}\n\n=== Description ===\n\nA blind Cyclops awakens the princess ([[Jean Grey]]) from her sleep, only to find that Wolverine is determined to keep her under her spell, or worse, dead.\n\n== Part 4 ==\n\n=== Specs ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Release Date\n! Written By\n! Art By \n! # of Pages\n|-\n| October, 2006\n| C.B.Cebulski\n| Kei Kobayashi\n| 32 Full Color Pages\n|}\n\n=== Description ===\nPulling upon some fairy tales that originated in [[New Orleans]], the love between [[Gambit (comics)|Gambit]] and [[Rogue (comics)|Rogue]] is re-created, though the roles are reversed, with Rogue/Anna as the ghost-communicating thief and Gambit on the side of the law with his partner, [[Bishop (comics)|Bishop]]. Mystique takes the form of the voodoo witch that sells Rogue's talent, along with her other daughter, Irene. Coming home after closing, Rogue is surprised to have a customer, [[Emma Frost]] asking for her services. It is then that Emma's intent is not to communicate with the dead, but to control them, and she, along with the members of Hellfire will stop at nothing do so.<ref>[http://www.marvel.com/catalog/?id=4476 Part 3]- Part 3</ref><ref>[http://www.popcultureshock.com/reviews.php?id=5663 Part 3 - 2nd ref] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071210030602/http://www.popcultureshock.com/reviews.php?id=5663 |date=December 10, 2007 }}- 2nd Ref</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{comicbookdb|type=title|id=6935|title=''X-Men Fairy Tales''}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.coverbrowser.com/covers/x-men-fairy-tales Cover Art] - The cover art for the 4 comics.\n\n{{X-Comics}}\n\n[[Category:Comics based on fairy tales]]\n", "name_user": "TheSandDoctor", "label": "safe", "comment": "rm redundant title param", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X-Men_Fairy_Tales"}
{"title_page": "Ingrid van Biezen", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Ingrid van Biezen\n| image        = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date   = 1969\n| birth_place  = \n| death_date   = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|death date\u2020|birth date\u2020}} -->\n| death_place  = \n| nationality  = [[Netherlands|Dutch]]\n| other_names  = \n| alma_mater   = [[Leiden University]]\n| occupation   = [[Professor]] of [[comparative politics]], [[Leiden University]]\n| years_active =\n| known_for    = \n}}\n'''Ingrid van Biezen''' (born 1969) is [[Professor]] of [[Comparative Politics]] at [[Leiden University]],<ref name=CV>{{cite web|url=http://media.leidenuniv.nl/legacy/2012---november.pdf |title=CV - Ingrid van Biezen|publisher=Leiden University|accessdate=8 January 2015}}</ref> and the editor of the [[political science]] journal ''[[Acta Politica]]''.\n\nHer research interests include comparative [[European politics]], [[political parties]] and party systems in [[Europe]], [[democratisation]], [[Southern Europe]], and post-[[Communism|communist]] politics.<ref name=\"CV\"/>\n\n== Education ==\nIngrid van Biezen studied for her masters and her [[PhD]] at [[Leiden University]].<ref name=CV/>  \n\n== Career ==\nFrom 2000 to 2009 she was based in the Department of Political Science and International Studies at the [[University of Birmingham]].<ref name=\"CV\"/>\n\nShe is currently directing a large comparative research project (Re-conceptualizing democracy) on political parties and democracy through a focus on party law.<ref name=Party>{{cite web | title= Party law in modern Europe: the legal regulation of political parties in post-war Europe | url= http://www.partylaw.leidenuniv.nl/ | publisher= [[Leiden University]] | accessdate= 8 January 2015 }}</ref> The project is funded by the [[European Research Council]].<ref name=ERC>{{cite web|title=Re-conceptualizing party democracy|url=http://erc.europa.eu/re-conceptualizing-party-democracy|publisher=European Research Council|accessdate=8 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n=== Books ===\n* {{cite book | last = van Biezen | first = Ingrid | title = Financing political parties and election campaigns : guidelines | publisher = Council of Europe Pub | location = Strasbourg | year = 2003 | isbn = 9789287153562 }}\n* {{cite book | last = van Biezen | first = Ingrid | title = Political parties in new democracies party organization in Southern and East-Central Europe | publisher = Palgrave Macmillan | location = Basingstoke New York | year = 2003 | isbn = 9781403903075 }}\n\n=== Journal articles ===\n* {{Cite journal | last = van Biezen | first = Ingrid | title = Building party organisations and the relevance of past models: The communist and socialist parties in Spain and Portugal | journal = [[West European Politics]] | volume = 21 | issue = 2 | pages = 32\u201362 | doi =  10.1080/01402389808425244| date = 1998 | ref = harv }}\n* {{Cite journal | last = van Biezen | first = Ingrid | title = The place of parties in contemporary democracies | journal = [[West European Politics]] | volume = 26 | issue = 3 | pages = 171\u2013184 | doi = 10.1080/01402380312331280648 | date = 2003 | ref = harv }}\n* {{Cite journal | last1 = van Biezen | first1 = Ingrid | last2 = Molenaar | first2 = Fransje | title = The Europeanisation of party politics? Competing regulatory paradigms at the supranational level | journal = [[West European Politics]] | volume = 35 | issue = 3 | pages = 632\u2013656 | doi = 10.1080/01402382.2012.665744 | date = 2012 | ref = harv }}\n* {{Cite journal | last1 = van Biezen | first1 = Ingrid | last2 = Mair | first2 = Peter | last3 = Poguntke | first3 = Thomas | author-link2 = Peter Mair | title = Going, going, ... gone? The decline of party membership in contemporary Europe | journal = [[European Journal of Political Research]] | volume = 51 | issue = 1 | pages = 24\u201356 | doi = 10.1111/j.1475-6765.2011.01995.x | date = January 2012 | ref = harv }}\n* {{Cite journal | last1 = van Biezen | first1 = Ingrid | last2 = Borz | first2 = Gabriela  | title = Models of party democracy: patterns of party regulation in post-war European constitutions | journal = European Political Science Review | volume = 4 | issue = 3 | pages = 327\u2013359 | doi = 10.1017/S1755773911000294 | date = November 2012 | ref = harv | url = https://strathprints.strath.ac.uk/44911/1/Biezen_Borz_EPSR2012.pdf }}\n* {{Cite journal | last1 = van Biezen | first1 = Ingrid | last2 = Helen | first2 = Wallace | author-link2 = Helen Wallace | title = Old and new oppositions in contemporary Europe | journal = Government and Opposition | volume = 48 | issue = 3 | pages = 289\u2013313 | doi = 10.1017/gov.2013.11 | date = July 2013 | ref = harv }}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.socialsciences.leiden.edu/politicalscience/organisation/faculty/biezen.html Homepage at Leiden University]\n*{{worldcat id|lccn-nb2003-75288}}\n\n{{Subject bar|portal1=Biography|portal2=Politics|portal3=Netherlands}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Biezen, Ingrid van}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dutch political scientists]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Birmingham]]\n[[Category:Leiden University alumni]]\n[[Category:Leiden University faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Leiden]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Ingrid van Biezen\n| image        = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date   = 1969\n| birth_place  = \n| death_date   = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|death date\u2020|birth date\u2020}} -->\n| death_place  = \n| nationality  = [[Netherlands|Dutch]]\n| other_names  = \n| alma_mater   = [[Leiden University]]\n| occupation   = [[Professor]] of [[comparative politics]], [[Leiden University]]\n| years_active =\n| known_for    = \n}}\n'''Ingrid van Biezen''' (born 1969) is [[Professor]] of [[Comparative Politics]] at [[Leiden University]],<ref name=CV>{{cite web|url=http://media.leidenuniv.nl/legacy/2012---november.pdf |title=CV - Ingrid van Biezen|publisher=Leiden University|accessdate=8 January 2015}}</ref> and the editor of the [[political science]] journal ''[[Acta Politica]]''.\n\nHer research interests include comparative [[European politics]], [[political parties]] and party systems in [[Europe]], [[democratisation]], [[Southern Europe]], and post-[[Communism|communist]] politics.<ref name=\"CV\"/>\n\n== Education ==\nShe studied for her masters and her [[PhD]] at Leiden.<ref name=CV/>  \n\n== Career ==\nFrom 2000 to 2009 she was based in the Department of Political Science and International Studies at the [[University of Birmingham]].<ref name=\"CV\"/>\n\nShe is currently directing a large comparative research project (Re-conceptualizing democracy) on political parties and democracy through a focus on party law.<ref name=Party>{{cite web | title= Party law in modern Europe: the legal regulation of political parties in post-war Europe | url= http://www.partylaw.leidenuniv.nl/ | publisher= [[Leiden University]] | accessdate= 8 January 2015 }}</ref> The project is funded by the [[European Research Council]].<ref name=ERC>{{cite web|title=Re-conceptualizing party democracy|url=http://erc.europa.eu/re-conceptualizing-party-democracy|publisher=European Research Council|accessdate=8 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n=== Books ===\n* {{cite book | last = van Biezen | first = Ingrid | title = Financing political parties and election campaigns : guidelines | publisher = Council of Europe Pub | location = Strasbourg | year = 2003 | isbn = 9789287153562 }}\n* {{cite book | last = van Biezen | first = Ingrid | title = Political parties in new democracies party organization in Southern and East-Central Europe | publisher = Palgrave Macmillan | location = Basingstoke New York | year = 2003 | isbn = 9781403903075 }}\n\n=== Journal articles ===\n* {{Cite journal | last = van Biezen | first = Ingrid | title = Building party organisations and the relevance of past models: The communist and socialist parties in Spain and Portugal | journal = [[West European Politics]] | volume = 21 | issue = 2 | pages = 32\u201362 | doi =  10.1080/01402389808425244| date = 1998 | ref = harv }}\n* {{Cite journal | last = van Biezen | first = Ingrid | title = The place of parties in contemporary democracies | journal = [[West European Politics]] | volume = 26 | issue = 3 | pages = 171\u2013184 | doi = 10.1080/01402380312331280648 | date = 2003 | ref = harv }}\n* {{Cite journal | last1 = van Biezen | first1 = Ingrid | last2 = Molenaar | first2 = Fransje | title = The Europeanisation of party politics? Competing regulatory paradigms at the supranational level | journal = [[West European Politics]] | volume = 35 | issue = 3 | pages = 632\u2013656 | doi = 10.1080/01402382.2012.665744 | date = 2012 | ref = harv }}\n* {{Cite journal | last1 = van Biezen | first1 = Ingrid | last2 = Mair | first2 = Peter | last3 = Poguntke | first3 = Thomas | author-link2 = Peter Mair | title = Going, going, ... gone? The decline of party membership in contemporary Europe | journal = [[European Journal of Political Research]] | volume = 51 | issue = 1 | pages = 24\u201356 | doi = 10.1111/j.1475-6765.2011.01995.x | date = January 2012 | ref = harv }}\n* {{Cite journal | last1 = van Biezen | first1 = Ingrid | last2 = Borz | first2 = Gabriela  | title = Models of party democracy: patterns of party regulation in post-war European constitutions | journal = European Political Science Review | volume = 4 | issue = 3 | pages = 327\u2013359 | doi = 10.1017/S1755773911000294 | date = November 2012 | ref = harv | url = https://strathprints.strath.ac.uk/44911/1/Biezen_Borz_EPSR2012.pdf }}\n* {{Cite journal | last1 = van Biezen | first1 = Ingrid | last2 = Helen | first2 = Wallace | author-link2 = Helen Wallace | title = Old and new oppositions in contemporary Europe | journal = Government and Opposition | volume = 48 | issue = 3 | pages = 289\u2013313 | doi = 10.1017/gov.2013.11 | date = July 2013 | ref = harv }}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.socialsciences.leiden.edu/politicalscience/organisation/faculty/biezen.html Homepage at Leiden University]\n*{{worldcat id|lccn-nb2003-75288}}\n\n{{Subject bar|portal1=Biography|portal2=Politics|portal3=Netherlands}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Biezen, Ingrid van}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dutch political scientists]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Birmingham]]\n[[Category:Leiden University alumni]]\n[[Category:Leiden University faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Leiden]]\n", "name_user": "Rpgrogan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEducation:Removed ambiguity and added a link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ingrid_van_Biezen"}
{"title_page": "The Circle (French TV series)", "text_new": "{{short description|French reality television show}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name             = The Circle France\n| image                 = The Circle France.png\n| caption               = The official title screen for ''The Circle France''.\n| genre                 = [[Reality television|Reality competition]]\n| creative_director     = \n| presenter             = ''None''\n| narrated              = \n| country               = [[France]]\n| theme_music_composer  = \n| opentheme             = \n| language              = French\n| num_series            = 1\n| num_episodes          = 12\n| executive_producer    = \n| camera                = \n| runtime               = 37\u201351 minutes\n| channel               = [[Netflix]]\n| company               = [[Studio Lambert]]\n| distributor           = \n| picture_format        = \n| audio_format          = \n| first_aired           = {{Start date|2020|4|9}}\n| last_aired            = {{Start date|2020|4|9}}\n| related               = {{Plainlist|\n* ''[[The Circle (British TV series)|The Circle UK]]''\n* ''[[The Circle (American TV series)|The Circle US]]''\n* ''[[The Circle (Brazilian TV series)|The Circle Brazil]]''\n}}\n| website               = https://www.thecirclecasting.com/the-circle-france\n}}\n\n'''''The Circle France''''' (also known as '''''The Circle Game''''' in [[France]])<ref name=\"trailer\">{{cite web |title=Season 1 Trailer: The Circle France |url=https://www.netflix.com/watch/81189754?trackId=13752289&tctx=0%2C0%2C30a8b6b7-19b1-47c5-82ed-01092634917d-7331629%2C%2C&t=0 |website=netflix.com |publisher=Netflix |accessdate=26 March 2020 |language=French |date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> is an French [[Reality television|reality competition]] show, produced by [[Studio Lambert]] and Motion Content Group which first aired on [[Netflix]] in 9 April 2020 that is based on a [[The Circle (British TV series)|British TV series of the same name]].<ref name=\"deadline\">{{cite web |last1=White |first1=Peter |title='The Circle': Netflix Lines Up French & Brazilian Remakes As Studio Lambert Uses UK Hub For Reality Format |url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/the-circle-netflix-france-brazil-1202519369/ |website=deadline.com |publisher=Deadline |accessdate=16 October 2019 |date=18 December 2018}}</ref> Along with ''The Circle France'', Netflix also released separate versions of ''[[The Circle (franchise)|The Circle]]'' in the [[United States]] and [[Brazil]].<ref name=\"hollywood_reporter\">{{cite web |last1=Elise Sandberg |first1=Bryn |title=Netflix to Adapt U.K. Reality Series 'The Circle' |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/netflix-adapt-uk-reality-series-circle-1150330 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=6 June 2019}}</ref> The show bills itself as a game based around social media, with the concept that \"anyone can be anyone in ''The Circle''\". It has been compared to ''[[Big Brother (franchise)|Big Brother]]'' and ''[[Catfish: The TV Show|Catfish]]'' in format,<ref name=\"deadline\"/> as well as ''[[Black Mirror]]'' episode \"[[Nosedive (Black Mirror)|Nosedive]]\" with the concept of ratings.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Abdulbaki |first1=Mae |title=Netflix's New Reality Competition The Circle Is Already Super Popular In The U.K. |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/2480934/netflixs-new-reality-competition-the-circle-is-already-super-popular-in-the-uk |website=Cinema Blend |accessdate=29 September 2019 |date=26 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April 2020, the season was won by Romain Ben, who had played the game as himself, and won the [[Euro|\u20ac]]100,000 ({{USD|110000}}) prize that came along with it. \u00c9l\u00e9a was the runner-up.\n\n== Format ==\nThe contestants, or \"players\", move into the same apartment building. However, the contestants do not meet face-to-face during the course of the competition, as they each live in their own individual apartment. They communicate solely using their profiles on a specially-designed [[social media]] app that gives them the ability to portray themselves in any way they choose. Players can thus opt to present themselves as a completely different personality to the other players, a tactic otherwise known as [[catfishing]]; for example, one male player in the first season presented himself as a female identity, while another female contestant used photos of a woman she felt was more attractive.<ref name=\"polygon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/entertainment/2020/1/10/21058661/the-circle-review-netflix-new-reality-show-catfishing|title=Netflix's The Circle is the sweetest reality show about catfishing|first=Ben|last=Kuchera|language=en-us|date=10 January 2020|accessdate=10 January 2020|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the series, the contestants \"rate\" one another from first to last place. At the end of the ratings, their average ratings are revealed to one another from lowest to highest. Normally, the two highest-rated players become \"influencers\", while the remaining players will be at risk of being \"blocked\" by the influencers. However, occasionally there may be a twist to the blocking process \u2013 varying from the lowest rating players being instantly blocked, the identity of the influencers being a secret, or multiple players being blocked at one time. Blocked players are eliminated from the game, but are given the opportunity to meet one player still in the game in-person. Then, the day after a blocking, a video message is shown to the remaining players to reveal if they were real or fake.<ref name=\"polygon\"/>\n\nDuring the finale, the contestants rate each other one final time, where the highest rated player wins the game and [[Euro|\u20ac]]100,000 ({{USD|110000}}).<ref name=\"trailer\"/>\n\n== Players ==\nThe players were selected from the \"20\u201325 individuals\" being cleared to appear on the show, with the remaining people never leaving standby status and not appearing on the show.<ref name=\"variety interview 1\">{{cite web |last1=Turchiano |first1=Danielle |title='The Circle' Boss on Connecting 'People Who Otherwise Might Not Have Come into Contact with Each Other' \u2014 And Catfishing |url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/features/the-circle-netflix-american-tim-harcourt-catfish-interview-1203449625/ |website=variety.com |publisher=Variety |accessdate=2 January 2020 |date=1 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The first nine players were revealed on ''The Circle France''{{'}}s [[Instagram]] profile.<ref>{{cite web |author1=@circlegame |title=Qui d'autre ne peut pas attendre! \ud83d\ude4c regardez les joueurs entrer dans The Circle Tomorrow sur @NetflixFR |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-tq9EsAU9X/ |website=instagram.com |publisher=Instagram |accessdate=8 April 2020 |date=8 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The players' profiles were revealed as they introduced themselves on-screen during an episode.<ref name=\"insider\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.craveyoutv.com/exclusive-interview-whats-next-for-best-friend-bill-from-the-circle/|title=Exclusive Interview: What's Next for Best Friend Bill from 'The Circle'|last=Buczak|first=Lizzy|date=2020-02-25|website=CraveyouTV TV Show Recaps, TV Reviews, Spoilers, Interviews|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Name\n! Age\n! Hometown\n! Playing as\n! Entered\n! Exit\n! Status\n|-\n| Lou Baudry\n| 22\n| [[Marseille]]\n| Herself\n| Episode 1\n| Episode 2\n| style=\"background:#f4c7b8;\" | Blocked\n|-\n| Josette \"Jo\" Gu\u00e9rin\n| 78\n| ''Unknown''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Two friends playing jointly as 25-year-old \"Nicolas\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Episode 1\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Episode 4\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#f4c7b8;\" | Blocked\n|-\n| Monique\n| 75\n| ''Unknown''\n|-\n| C\u00e9dric Doumbe\n| 27\n| [[Bordeaux]]\n| Himself\n| Episode 1\n| Episode 6\n| style=\"background:#f4c7b8;\"